<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/19B*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
The location of Badacê is not known. The Eulaeus River cannot be recognized to‑day with certainty because of the great changes in the river system of lower Mesopotamia. It lay between the Tigris, with which it was connected by a


<A ID="p283x"></A>canal, and the Pasitigris, ran near Susa, and emptied into the Persian Gulf (Arrian, <I>Anabasis</I>, 7.7.1‑2)<!--</A>ARRIAN:ANABASIS-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/19B*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
Colon, probably identical with Celon
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#110.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Book 17.110.4)</A>, must be the chief city of Callonitis
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/5*.html#54.7
	"TARGET="Polybius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Polybius,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Polybius, 5.54.7)
	</A>
or Chalonitis
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/16A*.html#1
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, 16.1.1)</A>, called Kallonê by Kiepert on his map of the Persian Empire. In taking this route from Badacê to Ecbatana the army would march up the Tigris valley for some 250 miles before reaching the road from Babylon to Media and entering the mountains.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
